				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Devs...<a name="65875"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 6 04 8:15 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I would actually like to see a breakdown of what the developers spend their time on. If you look at the bug fixes reported with patches it doesn't seem like there are a lot of them.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I don't think the problem is the developers anyway.
<br />

<br />
The biggest problem is lack of vision. Lack of fresh ideas. Lack of innovation. Lack of creativity. This is the sole responsibility of the game designers. All blame can be laid at their door.
<br />

<br />
Instead of diversifying they narrowed the focus.
<br />

<br />
They had a whole wide open world and slowly, expansion by expansion, they have been building walls around themselves and now there is nowhere to go but up. Unfortunately the game just doesn't scale well anymore. It is too slow to climb all the way to the top using the stairs. It is too slow to go back down and use the elevator to get to the top as you miss out on all the best purchases along the way. You can still shop at the top floor shops but you need the help of loads of other shoppers. Why bother? Shopping is not fun anymore, you know what you are going to get. You just go for the window displays.
<br />

<br />
Possible reasons for bugs not being fixed:
<br />

<br />
Teams not properly established or not properly managed. For instance: 
<br />
Support team -&gt; existing content
<br />
Expansion team -&gt; new content
<br />
Then a handover phase to pass new content to support team.
<br />

<br />
Inexperienced support team: Fix/impact analysis taking long.
<br />

<br />
Red tape: Assessment/approval/review of change take long.
<br />

<br />

<br />
I am sure SOE don't lack quality in their developers. You just need to be at least a decent coder to do most bug fixes. Specialists are required for technical design of new features, performance tuning, etc. Your normal developers channel all their changes through the developers that review code with the focus on performance, impact analysis, etc.
<br />

<br />
As for whining and bitching on message boards you employ the following:
<br />
Customer reps: Flame walls, sift through the crap and come up with the goods that go to the designers to ponder.
<br />

<br />
Designers: Design new features/content with the focus on balance and future proofing. If we take characters/mobs up to this level in this expansion will it be balanced? Do we leave enough room to grow for years to come?
<br />

<br />
Developers: Implement the design.
<br />

<br />
Note that the developers and designers will work together and revisit issues all the time. There should also be feedback from the designers back to the customer reps and decisions will be made what to tell the customers.
<br />

<br />
I just think that somewhere along the line the designers dug EQ into a hole.
<br />

<br />
Diddili Squawt</span></td>
